16/06/2010
PODGORICA, Montenegro -- Foreign ministers of countries in the Central European Initiative (CEI) agreed on Tuesday (June 15th) that the organisation should boost co-operation with other regional initiatives and with the EU. 
They also confirmed the EU prospects of all Western Balkan countries. 
After the meeting in Budva, Italy's top diplomat, Franco Frattini, said the CEI should strengthen its economic dimension and in the future, should promote co-operation with the support of the EU and European finance organisations. 
Montenegro, as current chairman of the CEI, hosted the foreign ministers of Italy, Serbia, Albania, Slovakia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, as well as representatives of the other member countries. 
(Tanjug, Radio Free Europe, RTCG, Beta - 15/06/10)
